This exercise is commonly used to improve squat form and increase lower body strength.

intermediate.name: dumbbell lateral lunge reach
intermediate.description: The dumbbell lateral lunge reach is a lower body exercise that primarily targets the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. It also engages the core and improves balance and stability. To perform the exercise, stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and hold a dumbbell in each hand. Step your left foot out to the side and lunge to the left while reaching the dumbbells down towards your left foot. Keep your chest up and your back straight. Return to the starting position and repeat on the other side.

intermediate.name: dumbbell front rack squat
intermediate.description: The dumbbell front rack squat is a lower body exercise that primarily targets the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. It also engages the core and improves upper body strength and stability. To perform the exercise, hold a dumbbell in each hand and bring them up to shoulder height, resting them on the front of your shoulders. Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and squat down, keeping your weight in your heels and your chest up. Return to the starting position and repeat.

intermediate.name: dumbbell offset squat
intermediate.description: The dumbbell offset squat is a lower body exercise that primarily targets the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. It also engages the core and improves balance and stability. To perform the exercise, hold a dumbbell in one hand and rest it on your shoulder. Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and squat down, keeping your weight in your heels and your chest up. Return to the starting position and repeat on the other side.

advanced.description: The barbell front rack step-up is a single-leg strength exercise that targets the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. It involves stepping up onto an elevated surface (such as a bench or step) with one foot while holding a barbell across the front of the shoulders.

advanced.name: barbell heels up back squat
advanced.description: The barbell heels-up back squat is a variation of the traditional barbell back squat that requires the lifter to raise their heels off the ground. This variation shifts more of the load onto the quads and can be helpful for lifters with limited ankle mobility.

advanced.name: barbell reverse deadlift
advanced.description: The barbell reverse deadlift is an advanced lower body exercise that primarily targets the quadriceps, glutes, and hamstrings. This exercise involves standing on a raised platform and performing a deadlift movement in reverse, pulling the barbell up towards the hips.

advanced.name: bodyweight reverse step up
advanced.description: The bodyweight reverse step up is an advanced lower body exercise that primarily targets the quadriceps, glutes, and hamstrings. This exercise involves stepping up onto a raised platform in reverse, with one leg at a time, while keeping the core engaged and maintaining balance.

advanced.name: barbell zercher squat
advanced.description: The barbell zercher squat is an advanced lower body exercise that primarily targets the quadriceps, glutes, and hamstrings. This exercise involves holding a barbell in the crook of the elbows and performing a squat movement while maintaining an upright posture and engaging the core.

advanced.name: dumbbell goblet curtsy lunge
advanced.description: The dumbbell goblet curtsy lunge is an advanced lower body exercise that primarily targets the quadriceps, glutes, and hamstrings. This exercise involves holding a dumbbell at chest level and stepping one foot behind and across the other leg, while bending both knees to lower the body and engage the muscles of the lower body.

advanced.name: dumbbell goblet lateral lunge
advanced.description: The dumbbell goblet lateral lunge is a great exercise for developing strength and flexibility in the lower body. Start by holding a dumbbell in front of your chest with both hands, and step laterally to one side, bending your knee and lowering your body until your thigh is parallel to the ground. Then push back up to the starting position and repeat on the other side. This exercise targets the quads, glutes, and hamstrings.

advanced.name: dumbbell front rack pause squat
advanced.description: The dumbbell front rack pause squat is a challenging exercise that targets the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. Hold a pair of dumbbells at shoulder height with your elbows up and palms facing each other. Lower your body into a squat, pausing at the bottom for a few seconds before pushing back up to the starting position. Make sure to keep your chest up and your knees in line with your toes throughout the movement.

advanced.name: dumbbell heels up narrow goblet squat
advanced.description: The dumbbell heels up narrow goblet squat is a variation of the goblet squat that places more emphasis on the quads. Hold a dumbbell with both hands at chest height, and lift your heels off the ground. Lower your body into a squat, keeping your feet close together and your knees in line with your toes. Push back up to the starting position and repeat for several reps.

advanced.name: single arm overhead squat
advanced.description: The single arm overhead squat is an advanced lower body exercise that primarily targets the quads, while also engaging the core and upper body. To perform this exercise, stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in one hand above your head. Slowly lower your body down into a squat position while keeping the weight above your head, then return to the starting position. Repeat for desired number of repetitions before switching sides.

advanced.name: plate single leg deadlift
advanced.description: The plate single leg deadlift is an advanced lower body exercise that primarily targets the quads and hamstrings, while also engaging the core and glutes. To perform this exercise, stand with one foot on a weight plate and the other foot planted firmly on the ground. Hold a weight plate in front of your body with both hands. Slowly lower your body down into a deadlift position while keeping the weight plate close to your body, then return to the starting position. Repeat for desired number of repetitions before switching sides.

advanced.name: kettlebell single leg deadlift
advanced.description: The kettlebell single leg deadlift is an advanced lower body exercise that primarily targets the hamstrings and glutes, while also engaging the core and quads. To perform this exercise, stand with one foot planted firmly on the ground and hold a kettlebell in the opposite hand. Slowly lower your body down into a deadlift position while keeping the kettlebell close to your body, then return to the starting position. Repeat for desired number of repetitions before switching sides.

beginner.name: walk on treadmill
beginner.description: A treadmill is a fitness machine that allows you to walk, jog, or run indoors while simulating the motion of walking or running outdoors. The machine typically has a conveyor belt that moves at varying speeds and inclines, allowing users to control the intensity and duration of their workouts.

beginner.name: elliptical
beginner.description: An elliptical machine, also known as a cross trainer, is a piece of fitness equipment that simulates the motion of running, walking, or stair climbing while putting less stress on the joints. It typically consists of two pedals that move in an elliptical pattern, and can be adjusted to simulate different levels of resistance and intensity.

beginner.name: stationary bike
beginner.description: A stationary bike, also known as an exercise bike, is a piece of fitness equipment that simulates the motion of riding a bicycle while staying in place. It typically consists of a seat, pedals, and handlebars, and can be adjusted to simulate different levels of resistance and intensity. Stationary bikes are popular in gyms and fitness centers, and can also be used at home for cardiovascular exercise and lower body conditioning.

intermediate.name: burpees
intermediate.description: Burpees are a high-intensity exercise that involves a combination of strength and cardio movements. They are popular in fitness classes and workouts because they can be performed almost anywhere and require no equipment.

intermediate.name: stair climber
intermediate.description: A stair climber, also known as a stair stepper or step machine, is a fitness machine that simulates climbing stairs. It typically consists of a set of pedals or steps that move up and down, creating a repetitive motion similar to climbing stairs. Stair climbers provide a low-impact cardiovascular workout that targets the muscles in the lower body, including the quadriceps, hamstrings, calves, and glutes.
